<section xml:id="section-week7-activity">
  <title>Week 7 Activity</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-inversion">
    <title>Inversion</title>
    <p>
      All row reductions in these activity were done with Wolfram
      Alpha. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the inverse of this matrix. Check by matrix
          multiplication that the product of the matrix and its
          inverse (in both orders!) is the identity.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              7 \amp 0 \\
              -5 \amp 4 
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I write the extended matrix with the original matrix and the
          identity.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{array}{cc|cc}
              7 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
              -5 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
            \end{array} \right)
          </me>
          I row reduce this extended matrix.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{array}{cc|cc}
              1 \amp 0 \amp \frac{4}{28} \amp 0 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{5}{28} \amp \frac{1}{4} \\
            \end{array} \right)
          </me>
          The left side of the extended matrix reduces to the
          identity, so the right side is the inverse matrix.
          Then I check the two products. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{1}{28} \left( \begin{matrix}
                4 \amp 0 \\
                -5 \amp -7 
              \end{matrix} \right)
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                7 \amp 0 \\
                -5 \amp -4 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp 1 \\
              \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                7 \amp 0 \\
                -5 \amp -4 
              \end{matrix} \right)
              \frac{1}{28} \left( \begin{matrix}
                4 \amp 0 \\
                -5 \amp -7 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp 1 \\
              \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Both products are the identity of the matrix, so this is the
          correct inverse. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the inverse of this matrix. Check by matrix
          multiplication that the product of the matrix and its
          inverse (in both orders!) is the identity.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix} 
              3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
              -3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
              2 \amp 1 \amp -4 
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I write the extended matrix with the original matrix and the
          identity.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
              3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
              -3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
              2 \amp 1 \amp -4 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 
            \end{array} \right)
          </me>
          I row reduce this extended matrix.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
              1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \frac{4}{11} \amp \frac{1}{11} \amp
              \frac{1}{11} \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \frac{-12}{11} \amp \frac{-14}{11} \amp
              \frac{-3}{11} \\
              0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{-1}{11} \amp \frac{-3}{11}
              \amp \frac{-3}{11} 
            \end{array} \right)
          </me>
          The left side reduces to the identity matrix, so the right
          side is the inverse matrix.  Then I check the two products. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{1}{11} \left( \begin{matrix}
                4 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
                -12 \amp -14 \amp -3 \\
                -1 \amp -3 \amp -3
              \end{matrix} \right)
              \left( \begin{matrix}
              3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
              -3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
              2 \amp 1 \amp -4 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
              \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
              3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
              -3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
              2 \amp 1 \amp -4 
              \end{matrix} \right)
              \frac{1}{11} \left( \begin{matrix}
                4 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
                -14 \amp -14 \amp -3 \\
                -1 \amp -3 \amp -3
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
              \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Both products are the identity of the matrix, so this is the
          correct inverse. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
