  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-kernels-images">
    <title>Kernels and Images</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p> 
          Calculate the kernel and image of this matrix. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              2 \amp 3 \\
              -3 \amp 2 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The kernel is the solution to the system with all constants
          as zero. Here is the matrix of that system.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{array}{cc|c}
              2 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\
              -3 \amp 2 \amp 0 
            \end{array} \right) 
          </me>
          I row reduce this system. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{array}{cc|c}
              1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 0 
            \end{array} \right) 
          </me>
          The only solution is the zero vector. 
          <me>
            \Ker \left( \begin{matrix}
              2 \amp 3 \\
              -3 \amp 2 
            \end{matrix} \right) = \left\{ \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \\ 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) \right\}
          </me>
          The image is the span of the columns. I put the columns as
          rows in a matrix and row reduce (without exchanging rows). 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              2 \amp -3 \\
              3 \amp 2 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          I row reduce this matrix.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              1 \amp 0 \\
              0 \amp 1 
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </me>
          I see that all of these are linearly independent. I
          write the image as the span of the linearly independent
          columns. 
          <me>
            \Image \left( \begin{matrix}
              2 \amp 3 \\
              -3 \amp 2 
            \end{matrix} \right) = \Span \left\{ \left( \begin{matrix}
              2 \\ -3 
            \end{matrix} \right), 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              3 \\ 2
            \end{matrix} \right) \right\} 
          </me>
          Alternatively, I could simply say that the image is all of
          <m>\RR^2</m>, since these two vectors span the whole space.  
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p> 
