  <subsection xml:id="subsection-week7-proofs">
    <title>Proof Questions</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> be <m>n \times n</m> invertible
          matrices. Prove that 
          <me>
            (MN)^{-1} = N^{-1} M^{-1} 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There are a number of ways to argue this. I could write out
          general matrices and argue algebraically, but that seems
          very difficult and cumbersome. Instead, I'd like to give a
          geometric argument. (Such an argument is not as formal but,
          depending on the context, could still be considered a
          proof.)
        </p>
        <p>
          If I interpret <m>MN</m> as a transformation <m>\RR^n
          \rightarrow \RR^n</m>, I apply <m>N</m> first, and then I
          apply <m>M</m> (composition works from right to left). Since
          both are invertible matrices, I can reverse both processes.
          If I wanted to reverse the composition, I would have to
          start with the last thing I did, which is <m>M</m>.
          Therefore, the first step in the inverse would be
          <m>M^{-1}</m>. Then I would get back to the point after I
          applied <m>N</m>, so the next thing to do would be
          <m>N^{-1}</m>. The way to write the composition of
          <m>M^{-1}</m> and <m>N^{-1}</m> would be
          <m>N^{-1}M^{-1}</m>. Therefore, I have proven that the
          inverse of <m>MN</m> should be the composition
          <m>N^{-1}M^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>M</m> be a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix. Assume that the
          kernel of <m>M</m> is 2 dimensional. Prove that <m>M</m> can
          have at most one linearly independent column. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I can use the proposition that the kernel and the image have
          dimensions that add to the dimension of the domain. I know
          the dimension of the kernel is <m>2</m>, and the dimension of
          the domain is <m>3</m>. Therefore, the dimension of the
          image must be <m>1</m>. But I also know that the image is
          the span of the columns. Since the image has dimension 1,
          the span of the columns has dimension 1. This means that
          there is only one linearly independent column since all the
          other columns are in the same line and thus multiples of the
          chosen column. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
